.TH NOISSH 1 "2026-06-18" "noissh 0.4.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
noissh \- resilient remote shell over the Noise Protocol Framework (client)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B noissh
.RB [ \-\-ssh ]
.RB [ \-\-port
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-server\-cmd
.IR CMD ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-install ]
.RB [ \-D
.IR SPEC ]
.RB [ \-\-exec
.IR CMD ]
.RI [ user @] host
.RB [ \-\-
.IR "ssh args" ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B noissh
connects to a
.BR noisshd (1)
server and runs an interactive login shell that survives packet loss, high
latency, IP changes, NAT rebinding, and laptop sleep/resume without
reconnecting. All cryptography uses the Noise Protocol Framework
.RB ( Noise_XX_25519_ChaChaPoly_BLAKE2s ).
The interactive shell rides unreliable latest\-wins datagrams and a client\-side
predictive\-echo engine, giving an instant feel even on poor links.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-ssh
Bootstrap the server over SSH: run
.B ssh
.I host noisshd --one-shot
to obtain the UDP port and the server's ephemeral public key, then connect over
Noise/UDP. No pre\-shared
.I authorized_keys
entry is required. If
.B noisshd
is not yet installed on the remote, the first connect installs it automatically:
the published installer is run over the same SSH session, detecting the remote
OS/arch, downloading the matching prebuilt release binary, verifying its SHA\-256
checksum, and installing it into
.IR ~/.local/bin ,
after which the handshake is retried. This applies only to the default server
command and is skipped when
.B \-\-server\-cmd
is set. The install step requires
.BR curl (1)
or
.BR wget (1)
on the remote.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-install
Disable the automatic remote install performed by
.BR \-\-ssh .
A missing
.B noisshd
then fails the connection instead of being installed.
.TP
.BI \-\-port " N"
UDP port for a direct connection to a standalone server (default 51820).
.TP
.BI \-\-server\-cmd " CMD"
Remote server command used with
.BR \-\-ssh
(default
.IR noisshd ).
.TP
.BI \-L " LPORT:HOST:PORT"
Local port forward: connections to
.IR 127.0.0.1:LPORT
on this machine are tunnelled, over the resilient session, to
.IR HOST:PORT
reachable from the server. May be repeated. Implies forward\-only (no shell).
.TP
.BI \-R " RPORT:HOST:PORT"
Remote port forward: the server listens on
.IR 127.0.0.1:RPORT
and tunnels accepted connections back to this client for delivery to
.IR HOST:PORT .
May be repeated. Implies forward\-only (no shell).
.TP
.BI \-D " [BIND:]PORT"
Dynamic port forward: run a local SOCKS proxy on
.I PORT
(bound to loopback unless
.I BIND
is given) whose connections are tunnelled, over the resilient session, to the
host and port each client requests, resolved via the server. The proxy speaks
SOCKS5 (no authentication) and SOCKS4/4a, CONNECT only. May be repeated. Implies
forward\-only (no shell).
.TP
.BI \-\-exec " CMD"
Run
.I CMD
on the server non\-interactively instead of opening a shell, then exit. The
command's standard output and standard error are streamed separately to yours,
your standard input is forwarded until EOF, and noissh exits with the command's
exit status. Output is byte\-for\-byte (no PTY/terminal processing), so it is safe
to redirect or pipe. Mutually exclusive with an interactive shell. Refused by a
standalone daemon configured with a
.B \-\-user
privilege drop.
.TP
.BI \-\-put " LOCAL:REMOTE"
Upload local file
.I LOCAL
to path
.I REMOTE
on the server, then exit. The spec is split on the first colon. Transfers run
over the resilient session and are mutually exclusive with an interactive shell
and with
.BR \-L / \-R .
.TP
.BI \-\-get " REMOTE:LOCAL"
Download server file
.I REMOTE
to local path
.IR LOCAL ,
then exit. The spec is split on the first colon. Transfers run over the
resilient session and are mutually exclusive with an interactive shell and with
.BR \-L / \-R .
.TP
.BR \-A ", " \-\-forward\-agent
Forward your local authentication agent to the interactive session. The server
exposes an
.I SSH_AUTH_SOCK
in the shell's environment whose connections tunnel back to your local agent, so
remote
.BR git / ssh
can use your local keys without copying them to the server. Requires
.I SSH_AUTH_SOCK
to be set locally; if it is unset, noissh warns and continues without agent
forwarding.
.TP
.BI \-\- " ssh args"
With
.BR \-\-ssh ,
pass all remaining arguments verbatim to
.BR ssh (1).
.SH AUTHENTICATION
On first contact the server's static public key is pinned (trust on first use)
in
.IR ~/.config/noissh/known_hosts ;
a later key change aborts the connection. The client's own static key lives in
.IR ~/.config/noissh/id
and must appear in the server's
.I authorized_keys
for direct connections.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/noissh/id
Client static X25519 keypair (mode 0600).
.TP
.I ~/.config/noissh/known_hosts
Pinned server public keys.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Exits with the remote shell's exit status, or non\-zero on connection failure.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Connect via SSH bootstrap:
.B noissh --ssh user@server
.TP
Direct connection on a custom port:
.B noissh --port 51820 user@server
.TP
Upload a file:
.B noissh --ssh user@server --put ./report.pdf /home/user/report.pdf
.TP
Download a file:
.B noissh --ssh user@server --get /var/log/app.log ./app.log
.TP
Dynamic SOCKS proxy on a local port:
.B noissh --ssh user@server -D 1080
.TP
Run a single remote command:
.B noissh --ssh user@server --exec "uname -a"
.TP
Interactive shell with agent forwarding:
.B noissh --ssh user@server -A
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR noisshd (1),
.BR ssh (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Gerardo Di Giacomo.
